## 2. OBSERVABILITY & STRUCTURED LOGGING (HIGHEST PRIORITY)

This is the most important section. An unobservable system is an untrustworthy system.

### 2.1 Log Levels — Use Them With Precision

```typescript
// TRACE — internal flow, hot paths, loop iterations. Disabled in production by default.
log.trace({ userId, query, params }, "Executing DB query")

// DEBUG — developer-facing context. Enable per-service in prod when investigating.
log.debug({ orderId, amount, currency }, "Processing payment intent")
log.debug({ cacheKey, ttl, hit: false }, "Cache miss, falling back to DB")
log.debug({ jobId, attempt, queue }, "Job dequeued for processing")
log.debug({ requestId, route, method, bodyBytes }, "Incoming request parsed")
log.debug({ connectionPool: pool.stats() }, "DB pool state before query")

// INFO — significant business events. Always on. Low volume.
log.info({ userId, planId, mrr }, "Subscription upgraded")
log.info({ invoiceId, amount, status: "paid" }, "Invoice payment succeeded")
log.info({ deployId, version, region }, "Deployment completed")

// WARN — degraded state, non-fatal issues that need attention.
log.warn({ retries, jobId, error: err.message }, "Job retrying after transient failure")
log.warn({ cacheHitRate, threshold: 0.8 }, "Cache hit rate below threshold")
log.warn({ p99Latency, slo: 200 }, "DB query latency approaching SLO breach")

// ERROR — something failed that shouldn't have. Always paged or tracked.
log.error({ err, requestId, userId, context }, "Payment charge failed unexpectedly")
log.error({ err, jobId, payload }, "Unrecoverable job failure, moving to DLQ")

// FATAL — process cannot continue. Triggers immediate alert + restart.
log.fatal({ err, config }, "Failed to connect to database on startup")
```

### 2.2 Structured Logging Rules

**Every log entry must be structured JSON. Never plain strings in production.**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT — structured, queryable, correlatable
log.debug({
  requestId,
  userId,
  action:     "charge.create",
  amount:     5000,
  currency:   "usd",
  customerId: "cus_abc123",
  duration:   142,
}, "Stripe charge created")

// ❌ WRONG — unqueryable, unsearchable, unfilterable
console.log(`Created charge for user ${userId} for $50`)
```

**Standard fields on every log entry:**
```typescript
interface LogContext {
  requestId:   string;       // Trace all logs for a single request
  traceId?:    string;       // Distributed trace ID (OpenTelemetry)
  spanId?:     string;       // Current span
  service:     string;       // Service name ("payments-api")
  version:     string;       // Deploy version / git SHA
  env:         string;       // "production" | "staging" | "development"
  userId?:     string;       // When authenticated
  orgId?:      string;       // When multi-tenant
  duration?:   number;       // ms — always log on completion
  err?:        SerializedError;
}
```

**Always log:**
- Request in + request out (with duration)
- Every external call (DB, cache, 3rd party API) with duration
- State transitions (job enqueued → dequeued → completed/failed)
- Auth decisions (granted/denied with reason)
- Config values at startup (sanitized — no secrets)
- Every retry attempt with attempt number and reason

**Never log:**
- Passwords, tokens, API keys, PII (SSN, full card numbers, full DOB)
- Raw request bodies unless specifically scrubbed
- Secrets of any kind — use `[REDACTED]` placeholders

### 2.3 Request Tracing

Every inbound request gets a `requestId`. Propagate it everywhere.

```typescript
// Middleware — assign and attach
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  req.requestId = req.headers["x-request-id"] ?? ulid();
  res.setHeader("x-request-id", req.requestId);
  req.log = logger.child({ requestId: req.requestId, route: req.path, method: req.method });
  next();
});

// Pass downstream — DB calls, queue jobs, outbound HTTP
await db.query(sql, params, { requestId: req.requestId });
await queue.publish("charge.create", payload, { meta: { requestId } });
await fetch(upstreamUrl, { headers: { "x-request-id": requestId } });
```

### 2.4 Performance Logging

Log durations for everything that touches I/O:

```typescript
const t = performance.now();
const result = await db.query(sql, params);
const duration = Math.round(performance.now() - t);

log.debug({ sql: sql.slice(0, 120), duration, rows: result.rowCount }, "DB query completed");

if (duration > 100) log.warn({ sql: sql.slice(0, 120), duration }, "Slow query detected");
```

### 2.5 Metrics

Emit metrics alongside logs. Don't rely on logs alone for alerting.

```typescript
// Counters
metrics.increment("api.requests.total",   { route, method, status });
metrics.increment("payments.charge.total", { currency, status });
metrics.increment("jobs.processed.total",  { queue, status });

// Histograms
metrics.histogram("api.request.duration",  duration, { route, method });
metrics.histogram("db.query.duration",     duration, { table, operation });
metrics.histogram("cache.operation.duration", duration, { operation, hit });

// Gauges
metrics.gauge("db.pool.active",    pool.activeCount);
metrics.gauge("queue.depth",       queue.size, { name: "payments" });
metrics.gauge("cache.hit_rate",    hitRate);
```

