## 12. CACHING STRATEGY

```typescript
// Cache-aside pattern (most common)
async function getCustomer(id: string): Promise<Customer> {
  const cacheKey = `customer:${id}`;

  const cached = await redis.get(cacheKey);
  if (cached) {
    log.debug({ customerId: id, cacheKey, hit: true }, "Cache hit");
    metrics.increment("cache.hit", { entity: "customer" });
    return JSON.parse(cached);
  }

  log.debug({ customerId: id, cacheKey, hit: false }, "Cache miss — querying DB");
  metrics.increment("cache.miss", { entity: "customer" });

  const customer = await db.query("SELECT * FROM customers WHERE id = $1", [id]);
  if (!customer) throw new NotFoundError("customer_not_found", "Customer not found");

  await redis.setex(cacheKey, 300, JSON.stringify(customer)); // 5 min TTL
  return customer;
}

// Cache invalidation — explicit on mutation
async function updateCustomer(id: string, data: UpdateCustomerInput) {
  const customer = await db.query("UPDATE customers SET ... WHERE id = $1", [id]);
  await redis.del(`customer:${id}`);
  log.debug({ customerId: id }, "Customer cache invalidated");
  return customer;
}
```

### Caching Rules
- Always set a TTL — never cache indefinitely.
- Cache reads, not writes.
- Invalidate explicitly on mutation — don't rely on TTL for consistency.
- Never cache errors or empty results unless intentionally (negative caching).
- Log every cache hit/miss with key and entity type.

